'''United Nations Memorial Cemetery''' ('''UNMCK''') ({{lang-ko|<U+C7AC><U+D55C><U+C720><U+C5D4><U+AE30><U+B150><U+ACF5><U+C6D0>}}; jae hahn UN ki nyum gong won),<ref>[http://www.unmck.or.kr/eng_index.php United Nations Memorial Cemetery, Korea]</ref> located at Tanggok in the [[Nam District, Busan|Nam District]],<ref name=1901st>{{cite web|title=Pusan (Korea) 1959|url=http://collections.lib.uwm.edu/cdm/ref/collection/agdm/id/688|publisher=[[University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee Libraries Digital Collections#Holdings of the American Geographical Society Library{{!}}American Geographical Society Library Digital Map Collection]]|author=1901st Engr. Topo. Bn., ROK Army|quote=Boundary Line Plan United Nations Memorial Cemetery}}; also see: [http://www.koreanwar2.org/kwp2/maps/l751_pdf/korean_war_project_smu_363.pdf Korea 1:50,000 Pusan Sheet 7019 III (1947)] and [http://www.koreanwar.org/html/korean_war_maps_results.html?id=259 Pusan <U+2013> 1947 <U+2013> AMS Map Sheet L751 <U+2013> 7109 III]</ref> [[Busan|City of Busan]],<ref group="nb">As a transliteration from [[Korean language|Korean]], the city name <U+BD80><U+C0B0> ({{IPA-ko|pusan}}) was typically spelled "Pusan" in [[McCune-Reischauer]] until 2000. The official [[Revised Romanization]] spells the name Busan. See {{cite web|url=http://geographic.org/geographic_names/name.php?uni=-1007276&fid=3437&c=south_korea |title=Pusan: South Korea |work=Geographical Names |accessdate=2011-08-15}}</ref>  [[South Korea|Republic of Korea]], is a burial ground for [[United Nations Command]] (UNC) [[Killed in action|casualties]] of the [[Korean War]].<ref group="nb">The Korean War started on 25 June 1950 when North Korean forces pushed south of the [[38th parallel north#Korea|38th parallel]] which [[Division of Korea|divided Korea]] following World War II. With authorization from the United Nations, forces from the United States and other nations pushed the North Koreans back to the north. When these UN forces approached China, Chinese forces intervened and the battlefront eventually stabilized along the 38th parallel. The [[s:Korean Armistice Agreement|Korean Armistice]] was signed on 27 July 1953 to end the fighting.</ref> It contains 2,300 graves and is the only [[United Nations]] cemetery in the world. Laid out over {{convert|14|hectare}}, the graves are set out in 22 sites designated by the nationalities of the buried servicemembers.<ref name=Clark>{{cite book|last=Clark|first=Donald N.|title=The [[Seoul Foreigners' Cemetery at Yanghwajin]] |url=http://seoul4ncemetery.org/documents/YANGHWAJIN_DonClark.pdf |date=September 1996|publisher=Seoul Union Church|location=Seoul, Korea|page=78|chapter=Part III: Smaller Foreign Cemeteries in the Provinces}}</ref>

==History==

===Temporary battlefield cemeteries and remains recovery===
The [[Korean War]] began when [[Korean People's Army Ground Force#History|North Korean People's Army]] forces moved south in June 1950. As the fighting progressed, temporary [[War grave|military cemeteries]] for battle casualties were established by United Nations forces near the towns of [[Taejon]] (9 July 1950), Kwan-ui (Kwan-ni),<ref name="Westover">{{cite book|last=Westover|first=John G.|coauthor=Cooper, Marcus E. ch. 1: "Division Supply Operations"; Kurtz, Jacob W. ch. 12: "Pukchon Cemetery" |title=Combat Support in Korea|year=1990|publisher=[[Center for Military History]]|location=Washington, DC|url=http://www.koreanwar2.org/kwp2/cmh/combat_support_in_korea.pdf|chapter=Part VII: Quartermaster Corps|pages=141<U+2013>150, 180<U+2013>183}}</ref> Kum-chon,<ref name="Westover" /> and [[Chilgok County|Sindong]].<ref name=Cook>{{cite journal |last=Cook |first=James C. |title=Graves Registration in the Korean Conflict |journal=The Quartermaster Review |date=March<U+2013>April 1953 |url=http://www.qmmuseum.lee.army.mil/korea/gr_korea.htm |publisher=Army Quartermaster Museum |location=Fort Lee, VA}}</ref> When the North Korean forces pushed towards Pusan, these cemeteries had to be abandoned.<ref name=Cook /> Later, as the [[Battle of Pusan Perimeter]] developed, temporary cemeteries were established at [[Masan]], [[Miryang]], and [[Taegu]], with a Pusan cemetery being established on 11 July 1950.<ref name="Coleman" /> As the fighting pushed into North Korea, temporary cemeteries were established in or near the towns of [[Kaesong]],<ref name="Westover" /> [[Sukehon]], [[Wonsan]], [[Pupchong]] ([[Pukchong County]]),<ref name="Westover" /> [[Battle of Chosin Reservoir#Battle|Yudarn-ni and Koto-ri]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Cannon |first=Florence |title=Our Honored Dead |journal=The Quartermaster Review |date=May<U+2013>June 1952 |url=http://www.memorialdayfoundation.org/articles/our-honored-dead.html |publisher=United States Quartermaster Museum & The Memorial Day Foundation |quote= [After July 1950], reports of burials were received from cemeteries in the Miryang, Taegu, Kaesong, Pyongyang, Sukehon, Wonsan, Pupchong, Hungnam, Yudarn, Koto-ri and Tanggok areas.}}</ref> Some 11 division-level cemeteries were established in the first two months of fighting<ref name=Anders>{{cite journal|last=Anders|first=Steven E.|title=With All Due Honors: A History of the Quartermaster Graves Registration Mission|journal=Quartermaster Professional Bulletin|date=September 1988|url=http://www.qmfound.com/grave.htm}}</ref> and later 5 UN military cemeteries were established in North Korea.<ref>{{cite web|title=POW March Routes and United Nations Cemeteries [map] |url=http://www.dtic.mil/dpmo/korea/maps/images/map_routes.jpg |publisher=[[Defense POW/Missing Personnel Office]]}}</ref>[[File:Graves registration service - korea.gif|left|thumbnail|A corporal from the 114th Graves Registration Co. fills out a Form 52B, giving information regarding a deceased American soldier at the U.N. Cemetery at [[Daegu, South Korea|Taegu]]. Nearby are a cross, a triangular unidentified soldier marker, and small bottle containing Form 1042 which is buried with the casualty. (US Army Photo, 23 January 1951)]]

At the beginning of the war, the nearest U.S. Army [[Mortuary Affairs#Korean War|mortuary affairs]] unit was the 108th Graves Registration Platoon in [[Yokohama, Japan]], which was searching for the remains of missing World War II American airmen.<ref name="Coleman">{{cite journal|last=Coleman|first=Bradley Lynn|title=Recovering the Korean War Dead, 1950<U+2013>1958: Graves Registration, Forensic Anthropology, and Wartime Memorialization|journal=[[The Journal of Military History]]|date=January 2008|volume=72|issue=1|pages=179<U+2013>222|publisher=Project Muse ([[Society for Military History]]) |issn=0899-3718 |url= http://www.smh-hq.org/jmh/jmhvols/721.html|doi=10.1353/jmh.2008.0013 }}</ref><ref name="Potter">{{cite book |last=Potter |first=Constance |title=A Companion to American Military History, Vol II |year=2010 |publisher=Wiley-Blackwell |isbn=978-1-4051-6149-7 |page=1039 |url=http://books.google.com/?id=6TctrNS2-34C&pg=PA1039&lpg=PA1039&dq=Tanggok+Pusan#v=onepage&q=Tanggok%20Pusan&f=false |coauthors=Deeben, John |editor= [[James C. Bradford|Bradford, James C.]] |chapter=67: Care for the Military Dead | oclc=316098909 }}</ref><ref>The only other American [[active duty]] graves registration unit was at [[Ft. Bragg, North Carolina]]. {{cite journal|last=Becker|first=James R.|title=United States Culture and Its Effects on Military Policy Regarding Mortuary Affairs |year=2004 |url=http://oai.dtic.mil/oai/oai?verb=getRecord&metadataPrefix=html&identifier=ADA428539 |publisher=[[US Army Command and General Staff College]] |location=Ft. Leavenworth, KS}}</ref> The 108th was reconfigured as the 114th Graves Registration Company and deployed to establish temporary cemeteries at [[Hungnam]], [[Pyongyang]], and Suchon as the fighting continued.<ref name="Coleman" /> Supporting the [[2nd Infantry Division (United States)#Korean War|2nd Infantry Division]] was the Graves Registration Section of the 2nd Quartermaster Company, which collected the remains of Allied and American soldiers to be further processed by the 148th Graves Registration Company.<ref>{{cite book |last=Alexander |first=Bevin R. |title=Combat Support in Korea |year=1951 |publisher=[[U.S. Army Center of Military History]] |url=http://www.history.army.mil/documents/Korea/KW-MHD/BA-60/ba-60.htm|chapter=Quartermaster Field Service Platoon in Action}}</ref> When UN forces launched the [[Inchon Invasion]] in September 1950, a platoon from the 565th Graves Registration Company accompanied them.<ref name="Coleman" /> Other mortuary affairs units included the 293rd Graves Registration Company, activated in April 1951.<ref name="Coleman" /> It was difficult to recover remains and conduct burials in Korea, due to the rugged geography and harsh climate, and the threat of [[unexploded ordnance]] and [[booby-traps]].<ref name=Dickon /><ref>{{cite book |last=Sledge |first=Michael |title=Soldier Dead: How We Recover, Identify, Bury, and Honor Our Military Fallen |year=2005 (2007) |publisher=Columbia University Press |location=New York |pages=40<U+2013>41, 58, 80, 190 |isbn=978-0-231-50937-4 |oclc= 60527603 }}</ref>

===Construction of the Tanggok cemetery===
Construction of the United Nations Military Cemetery (UNMC) at Tanggok began on 18 January 1951 and was carried out by hand-labor over a {{convert|28.2|hectare}} site.<ref name=Keene>{{cite journal|last=Keene|first=Judith|title=Below Ground: The Treatment of American Remains from the Korean War|journal=[[The Public Historian]]|date=February 2010|volume=32|issue=1|pages=58<U+2013>78|doi=10.1525/tph.2010.32.1.59|url=http://www.jstor.org/stable/10.1525/tph.2010.32.1.59|publisher=[[National Council on Public History]]|issn=0272-3433}}</ref> It was dedicated by General [[Matthew Ridgeway]] on 6 April 1951.<ref name=Cook /><!-- <ref>{{cite web|title=UN Memorial Cemetery|url=http://eng.koreanwar60.go.kr/20/2005000000.asp|publisher=The 60th Anniversary of the Korean War Commemoration Committee}}{{dead link|date=March 2014}}  May be a temporary problem. Will resolve as part of the GAR.</ref> --><ref name=Keene /> Graves Registration units then concentrated American and allied remains at Tanggok before they were permanently buried or repatriated.<ref name=Cook /><ref name="Potter" /> Besides burial services, refrigeration units to store remains were added,<ref name=Keene /> as were cremation facilities.<ref name="Colombia">Casualties from the [[National Army of Colombia#Korean War|Colombia Battalion]] were cremated at Tanggok by the American Graves Registration Service and then repatriated to Colombia in 1954. {{cite journal |last=Coleman |first=Bradley Lynn |title=The Colombian Army in Korea, 1950<U+2013>1954 |journal=[[The Journal of Military History]] |date=October 2005 |volume=69 |issue=4 |pages=1166<U+2013>1167 |publisher=Project Muse ([[Society for Military History]]) |issn=0899-3718 |url= http://muse.jhu.edu/login?auth=0&type=summary&url=/journals/journal_of_military_history/v069/69.4coleman.pdf |doi=10.1353/jmh.2005.0215 }}</ref> Today the 2,300 graves in the cemetery are set out in 22 sites designated by the nationalities of the buried servicemembers.<ref name=Clark />

===Post-armistice===
Following the signing of the [[Korean Armistice Agreement]] in July 1953, the United Nations Command sought to recover bodies interred in North Korean territory.<ref>{{cite web|title=Major Remains Concentrations in North Korea |url=http://www.dtic.mil/dpmo/korea/maps/documents/Major%20Remains%20Concentrations%20in%20North%20Korea.pdf |publisher=[[Defense POW/Missing Personnel Office]]}}; {{cite web|title=POW March Routes and U.N. Cemeteries |url=http://www.dtic.mil/dpmo/korea/maps/documents/POW%20March%20Routes%20and%20UN%20Cemeteries.pdf |publisher=[[Defense POW/Missing Personnel Office]]}}</ref> Cemeteries for POWs in North Korea were established at 16 POW camps.<ref>{{cite web|title=Major Remains Concentrations in North Korea [map] |url=http://www.dtic.mil/dpmo/korea/maps/images/map_remains07.jpg |publisher=[[Defense POW/Missing Personnel Office]]}}</ref>  From September to October 1954, the resulting exchange of casualties, dubbed [[Operation Glory]], between United Nations forces and the North Koreans resulted in 4,219 remains being recovered, of which 1,275 were non-US casualties.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Operation GLORY: Historical Summary |journal=Condensed from Graves Registration Division, Korean Communications Zone (KCOMZ) |date=Jul<U+2013>Dec 2004 |url=http://www.qmmuseum.lee.army.mil/korea/op_glory.htm|publisher=Army Quartermaster Museum|location=Fort Lee, VA}} Note: the calculation of remains comes from Coleman as the "Historical Summary" gives a total of 4,023 UN remains received.</ref> (Also exchanged were the remains of approximately 14,000 North Korean and Chinese casualties.)<ref>{{cite book |last=Cole |first=Paul M. |title=POW/MIA Issues Volume 1, The Korean War |year=1994 |publisher=National Defense Research Institute |location=Santa Monica, CA |isbn=978-0-8330-1482-5 |page=68 |url=http://www.rand.org/content/dam/rand/pubs/monograph_reports/2006/MR351.1.pdf |chapter=Three: Efforts to Recover and Account for Korean War Casualties |oclc = 855303293}}</ref> From 1950 to 1954, approximately 11,000 casualties were interred at UNMC, which was maintained by the United States Army Graves Registration Agency.<ref name="status" /><ref>{{cite book|last=Nahm|first=Andrew W.|title=Historical Dictionary of the Republic of Korea |year=2004 |publisher=Scarecrow Press |location=Lantham, MD |isbn=0-8108-4949-6 |page=173|coauthors=Hoare, James E. |oclc=54081516}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Conference Series: Canada and the United Nations|year=1956|page=15|author=Department of External Affairs |location=Ottawa |oclc=}}</ref>

===Foundation as a United Nations cemetery and transfer to CUNMCK===
It was officially established as the United Nations Memorial Cemetery on 15 December 1955 with the passage of [[UN General Assembly Resolution]] 977(X).<ref>{{cite web|title=977(X). Establishment and maintenance of a United Nations Memorial Cemetery in Korea|url=http://www.worldlii.org/int/other/UNGARsn/1955/73.pdf|work=General Assembly <U+2013> Tenth Session; 557th plenary meeting|publisher=United Nations|pages=37<U+2013>38|date=15 December 1955}}; also see: [http://books.google.com/books?id=c7DXRhwHaVQC&pg=PA554&lpg=PA554&dq=united+nations+memorial+cemetery+korea&source=bl&ots=2CHEhvRzqu&sig=mwGgXe4AlaHqZWvovoi7rbmaQAE&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ubReUtDiM4qIiALziYGwDA&ved=0CFQQ6AEwAzgo#v=onepage&q=united%20nations%20memorial%20cemetery%20korea&f=false ''United Nations Juridical Yearbook 2003'']. p. 554. ISBN 978-92-1-133767-9</ref> Following the war, the cemetery was funded from the United Nations budget, but the Sino-Soviet world objected to this funding.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Gareau |first=Frederick H. |title=The Soviet Bloc and the United Nations System: the Quantitative Record |journal=[[Political Research Quarterly]] |date=June 1972 |volume=25 |issue=2 |pages=268<U+2013>94 |doi=10.1177/106591297202500209}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Lee |first=Chae-Jin |title=China and Korea: Dynamic Relations |year=1996 |publisher=Hoover Press |location=Stanford, CA |page=116 | isbn=978-0-8179-9421-1 |coauthors=Park, Doo-Bok |oclc= 34151310}}</ref> In 1973, the cemetery was transferred from the UN to the Commission for the United Nations Memorial Cemetery (CUNMCK), which is composed of representatives from the 11 countries who have servicemembers buried there.<ref name="Clark"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Cemeteries overseas |url=http://www.dva.gov.au/commems_oawg/OAWG/remembering_war_dead/Pages/korean%20war.aspx |work=Korean War |publisher=[[Australia Department of Veterans' Affairs]] |date=2012-08-30}}</ref>

===Cultural heritage and tourism===
The cemetery is designated as Site 359 in the listing of Registered Cultural Heritage Sites in Korea by the [[Cultural Heritage Administration of Korea]].<ref name="Site 359">{{cite web|title=UN Commemoration Park in Korea|url=http://english.cha.go.kr/english/search_plaza_new/EMapResultView.jsp?VdkVgwKey=79,03590000,21&strGuCode=17&strSidoCode=21 |work=Registered Cultural Heritage Site 359 |publisher=[[Cultural Heritage Administration of Korea]]}}</ref> Also, it is a visitor attraction for [[Pacific Rim]] tourists.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hutchinson|first=Garrie|title=Pilgrimage: A Traveler's Guide to Australia's Battlefields|year=2006|publisher=Black Inc.|location=Melbourne|isbn=978-1-86395-387-0 |page=384 |oclc=234310738}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Hall|first=Colin Michael|title=Tourism in the Pacific Rim: Development, Impacts, and Markets|year=1994|publisher=Longman Cheshire|location=Melbourne|isbn=978-0-470-23375-7|page=48|oclc=258617555 }}</ref> In 2011, [[United Nations Secretary-General]] [[Ban Ki-Moon]] described it as the only United Nations cemetery in the world.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ban|first=Ki-Moon|title=Remarks at UN Memorial Cemetery in Korea [as delivered] |url=http://www.un.org/apps/news/infocus/sgspeeches/statments_full.asp?statID=1398#.UnMXkZR4Ya7 |work= [[Ban Ki-Moon]]'s speeches |publisher=UN News Center |date=November 30, 2011}}</ref>

==Memorials==
[[File:A little Korean girl places a wreath of flowers on the grave of an American soldier, while Private First Class... - NARA - 530634.tif|right|thumbnail|250px|April 1951 <U+2013> a Korean girl places a wreath of flowers while an honour guard [[Present arms (command)|present arms]] at the United Nations cemetery in Pusan.]]
An [[Honour Guard]] from the [[Republic of Korea Army#Second Operational Command (<U+C721><U+AD70> <U+C81C>2<U+C791><U+C804><U+C0AC><U+B839><U+BD80>)|Republic of Korea 53rd Division]] carries out [[Flag-raising ceremony#Hoisting the flag|flag ceremonies]] daily.<ref>{{cite web|title=Korea Vet News|url=http://france-coree.pagesperso-orange.fr/eurokorvet/uk/can_newslet.htm|publisher=Korean War Commemoration Council of Canada}}</ref>

The UN Sculpture Park was established in October 2001 and twenty-nine permanent memorials are in the cemetery.<ref name="southafrica-embassy">{{cite web|title=UN Sculpture Park|url=http://southafrica-embassy.or.kr/eng/sankorea/korean_war(UNMCK).php|work=UNMCK|publisher=Republic of South Africa Embassy}}</ref> The memorials include:

* [[Commonwealth of Nations]] memorials:
** Australian Memorial<ref name=KWMemorials.org/><ref name="defenceanglicans">{{cite web|title=Remembering the Korean War|url=http://www.defenceanglicans.org.au/remembering-the-korean-war/|work=Ministry Stories|publisher=Defence Anglicans|accessdate=November 9, 2013|year=2013}}</ref>
** British Memorial <U+2013> dedicated 2010<ref>[http://www.unmck.or.kr/pop/eng_un_02_35.php UNMCK: British Memorial]</ref>
** Monument to Canadian Fallen <U+2013> an identical monument is located in downtown [[Ottawa]]<ref name=KWMemorials.org/><ref>{{cite web|title=Monument to Canadian Fallen (Korean War Monument)|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/eng/1380645149037|work=Public Art and Monuments|publisher=[[Canadian Heritage]], Government of Canada|date=October 25, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Canadian Korean War Veterans Participate in a Remembrance Ceremony at the United Nations Memorial Cemetery in the Republic of Korea|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/canadian-korean-war-veterans-participate-in-a-remembrance-ceremony-at-the-united-nations-memorial-cemetery-in-the-republic-of-korea-217300351.html|publisher=PR Newswire|date=28 July 2013|quote=[T]he names of the 516 Canadian soldiers who died&nbsp;... are written on the Wall of Remembrance.}}</ref>
**Commonwealth Memorial<ref>{{cite book|last=Summers|first=Julie|title=British and Commonwealth War Cemeteries|year=2010|publisher=Shire Publications|location=Oxford, UK|isbn=978-0-7478-0789-6|page=50|url=http://books.google.com/?id=PnT_8yIcTNAC&pg=PA50&lpg=PA50&dq=united+nations+memorial+cemetery+korea#v=onepage&q=united%20nations%20memorial%20cemetery%20korea&f=false|chapter=Commemoration of the War Dead Since 1945 |oclc=462882226 }}</ref> 
*** Commonwealth Missing in Action Memorial<ref name="defenceanglicans" />
** New Zealand Memorial <U+2013> designed by [[Warren and Mahoney]] architects and built of marble from the [[Coromandel Peninsula]]<ref>{{cite web|title=New Zealand Memorial in Korea|url=http://www.mch.govt.nz/nz-identity-heritage/national-monuments-war-graves/new-zealand-memorial-korea|work=National monuments & war graves|publisher=NZ Identity & Heritage|date=February 19, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Veterans To Attend Korean War Armistice Commemoration|url=http://www.airforce.mil.nz/about-us/news/media-releases/media-release.htm@guid=%7Ba12c2901-9c7c-47de-8c83-ce061ec99d62%7D.htm|work=Media Releases|publisher=New Zealand Defence Force|date=June 2013}}</ref> 
** South Africa Memorial <U+2013> the 2001 sculpture ''Reconciliation'' by South African sculptor [[Strijdom van der Merwe]], was created as part of the [[International Sculpture Symposium]]<ref name="southafrica-embassy" />
* French Memorial <U+2013> dedicated 2007<ref name=KWMemorials.org/><ref>[http://www.unmck.or.kr/pop/eng_un_02_34.php UNMCK: French Memorial]</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Quisefit|first=Laurent|title=The French Participation in the Korean War and the Establishment of a 'Path of Memory' in South Korea|journal=Societies|date=5 November 2013|volume=3|issue=4|pages=427<U+2013>444|doi=10.3390/soc3040427|url=http://www.mdpi.com/2075-4698/3/4/427|issn=2075-4698}}</ref>
* Greek Memorial <U+2013> dedicated 1961<ref name=KWMemorials.org/><ref>[http://www.unmck.or.kr/pop/eng_un_02_23.php UNMCK: Greek Memorial]</ref>
* Interfaith memorial chapel <U+2013> built by the United Nations Command in 1964<ref name=Clark />
* Main gate <U+2013> designed by Korean architect [[Kim Joong-up]] and built by the city of Busan in 1966<ref name=Clark /><ref name="Site 359" /> 
* Memorabilia display hall <U+2013> built by the UN in 1968<ref name=Clark />
* Norwegian Memorial<ref name=Haakon /><ref>{{cite web|title=Vice Minister [Foreign Affairs, Torgeir Larsen] Visits United Nations Memorial Cemetery in Korea|url=http://www.norway.or.kr/News_and_events/Current-affairs/News/Vice-Minister-Visits-United-Nations-Memorial-Cemetery-in-Korea/#.UmQBjJR4adO|publisher=The Royal Norwegian Embassy in Seoul|date=10.04.2013}}</ref>
* Philippine Memorial <U+2013> sponsored in 2009 by the [[Department of National Defense (Philippines)|Philippines Department of National Defense]]<ref name=KWMemorials.org/><ref>{{cite web|title=Filipino soldiers in Korean War honored|url=http://globalnation.inquirer.net/news/breakingnews/view/20110311-324804/Filipino-soldiers-in-Korean-War-honored|work=Inquirer Global Nation|publisher=The Inquirer Company|date=March 3, 2011}}</ref>
* Thai Memorial <U+2013> dedicated November 2008<ref name=KWMemorials.org/><ref>{{cite web|title=Bilateral Relations: Military cooperation|url=http://www.thaiembassy.org/seoul/en/relation|publisher=Royal Thai Embassy, Seoul|date=May 2, 2013}}</ref>
* Turkish Memorials I and II <U+2013> dedicated 1960, 1962, and 2008<ref name=KWMemorials.org/><ref>{{cite web|title=South Koreans, allies pay tribute to Turkish war effort|url=http://defence.pk/threads/south-koreans-allies-pay-tribute-to-turkish-war-effort.63383/|work=Daily News|publisher=Pakistan Defence|date=June 27, 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.unmck.or.kr/pop/eng_un_02_21.php UNMCK: Turkish Memorial I]; [http://www.unmck.or.kr/pop/eng_un_02_22.php UNMCK: Turkish Memorial II]</ref>
* UN Forces Monument <U+2013> dedicated 1978 and refurbished in 2007<ref name=KWMemorials.org/><ref>[http://www.unmck.or.kr/pop/eng_un_02_42.php UNMCK: UN Forces Monument]</ref>
* United States Korean War Memorial <U+2013> the [[Frank Gaylord]] sculpture was carved from [[Barre Granite]] at the [[Rock of Ages Corporation]] in [[Barre (town), Vermont|Barre, Vermont]], and dedicated under the auspices of the [[American Battle Monuments Commission]] in 2013<ref>{{cite web|title=Dedication of the U.S. Korean War Memorial in Busan, South Korea on July 28 |url=http://www.abmc.gov/events/KWMemorial.php |work=Events: |publisher=[[American Battle Monuments Commission]] |date=22 July 2013 |quote=This is the third memorial commemorating the Korean War created by ABMC.}}</ref><ref>[http://www.abmc.gov/memorials/memorials/kw.php Korean War Monument at Busan]</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Delcore|first=David|title=Barre granite is new, unique memorial in South Korea|url=http://www.vermonttoday.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/RH/20130928/NEWS01/709289956|work=Vermont Today|publisher=Rutland Herald}}</ref> 
* The Unknown Soldiers' Pathway<ref name=KWMemorials.org>[http://www.koreanwarmemorials.org/domestic/united-nations/united-nations-memorial-cemetery-in-korea/ Korean War Memorials: UN Memorial Cemetery in Korea]</ref>

The Wall of Remembrance, completed in 2006, has the names of the 40,896 United Nations casualties (killed and missing) inscribed on 140 marble panels.<ref name=KWMemorials.org/><ref>[http://www.unmck.or.kr/pop/eng_un_02_45.php UNMCK: Wall of Remembrance]</ref>

The UNMCK maintains a website in [[Korean language|Korean]], [[English language|English]], and [[Turkish language|Turkish (T<U+00FC>rk<U+00E7>e)]], which allows website visitors to post online flowers and tributary messages.<ref>[http://www.unmck.or.kr/eng_memory_07.php UNMCK: Cyber Flower Dedications] and [http://www.unmck.or.kr/bbs/board.php?bo_table=letter_eng UNMCK: Tributary Message]</ref>

==Notable graves==
[[File:Ereveld Tanggok.jpg|left|thumbnail|225px|The grounds today<!-- Photo was loaded in 2008, but has a 1987 timestamp. Best to leave date vague. -->]]
The cemetery contains the graves of 2,289 military personnel and 11 non-combatants. Amongst those are the graves of [[Bill Madden (GC)]], 3rd Battalion, Royal Australian Regiment, (who died as a prisoner of war), [[Kenneth Muir (VC)]] (killed in action in the [[Battle of Hill 282]] while serving with the [[Argyll and Sutherland Highlanders]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unmck.or.kr/eng_m_searchsol_view.php?uid=340806|title=Major Muir, K.|publisher=UN Memorial Cemetery, Korea}}</ref> and [[Philip Curtis|Philip Curtis (VC)]] (killed in action in the [[Battle of the Imjin River]] while serving with [[The Duke of Cornwall's Light Infantry]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unmck.or.kr/eng_m_searchsol_view.php?uid=331009|title=Lt. Curtis, P.K.E.|publisher=UN Memorial Cemetery, Korea}}</ref>  Also buried is Lt. Col. [[Charles Hercules Green|Charles Hercules Green (DSO)]], commander of the [[3rd Battalion, Royal Australian Regiment]], who was mortally wounded at [[Battle of Chongju (1950)|Battle of Chongju]] and died at nearby [[Anju, South Pyongan|Anju]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unmck.or.kr/eng_m_searchsol_view.php?uid=350810|title=Lt. Col. Green, Charles Hercules|publisher=UN Memorial Cemetery, Korea}}</ref> Dutch Lt. Col. [[:nl:Marinus Petrus Antonius den Ouden|Marinus Petrus Antonius den Ouden]], commander of the [[Regiment Van Heutsz]], was killed in action during [[Operation Roundup (1951)|Operation Roundup]] in 1951 and is buried with members of his regiment <U+2013> posthumously, den Ouden was received Netherlands' highest military award, the [[Military Order of William]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unmck.or.kr/eng_m_searchsol_view.php?uid=100301|title=Lt. Kol. Cdt. Ouden, M.P.A. den|publisher=UN Memorial Cemetery, Korea}}</ref> In the early days of the war, journalist [[Christopher Buckley (journalist)|Christopher Buckley]] died from a land mine explosion, and was subsequently buried at the cemetery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unmck.or.kr/eng_m_searchsol_view.php?uid=311002#|title=Mr. Buckley, C.|publisher=UN Memorial Cemetery, Korea}}</ref>

